# Public API Conventions

This project exposes a public REST API under `src/app/api/` consumed by the Next.js web app, a future mobile app, and any third-party client. All public routes must follow these conventions.

> New or changed public routes also need a matching MCP tool — **`mcp-route-handlers.mdc`**.

## Consistent Response Shape

Every route must return a uniform JSON envelope so clients can handle responses generically.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — consistent envelope
return NextResponse.json({ data: decks }, { status: 200 });
return NextResponse.json({ error: "Not found" }, { status: 404 });

// ❌ BAD — inconsistent shape
return NextResponse.json(decks);
return NextResponse.json({ message: "error" });
```

## Reusable `withAuth` Middleware

Rather than repeating auth checks in every handler, wrap handlers with `withAuth`.

```typescript
// src/lib/api/with-auth.ts
import { auth } from "@clerk/nextjs/server";
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";

type Handler = (
  req: NextRequest,
  context: { params: Promise<Record<string, string>>; userId: string }
) => Promise<NextResponse>;

export function withAuth(handler: Handler) {
  return async (
    req: NextRequest,
    context: { params: Promise<Record<string, string>> }
  ) => {
    const { userId } = await auth();
    if (!userId) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "Unauthorized" }, { status: 401 });
    }
    return handler(req, { ...context, userId });
  };
}
```

```typescript
// src/app/api/decks/route.ts
import { withAuth } from "@/lib/api/with-auth";
import { getDecksByUser } from "@/db/queries/decks";

export const GET = withAuth(async (_req, { userId }) => {
  const decks = await getDecksByUser(userId);
  return NextResponse.json({ data: decks });
});
```

## Query Parameters

Use `request.nextUrl.searchParams` — never parse `request.url` manually. Use consistent, industry-standard names such as `page`, `pageSize`, `limit`, `offset`, or `cursor`; do not invent route-specific pagination parameter names.

```typescript
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";

export const GET = withAuth(async (req, { userId }) => {
  const limit = Number(req.nextUrl.searchParams.get("limit") ?? 20);
  const offset = Number(req.nextUrl.searchParams.get("offset") ?? 0);
  const { items, totalItems } = await getDecksByUser(userId, { limit, offset });
  return NextResponse.json({
    data: items,
    metadata: { total_items: totalItems, per_page: limit },
    links: {
      next: "https://example.com/api/decks?limit=20&offset=20",
      prev: null,
      first: "https://example.com/api/decks?limit=20&offset=0",
      last: "https://example.com/api/decks?limit=20&offset=80",
    },
  });
});
```

## Pagination — Required for Collection Routes

All public API routes that return collections must support pagination. Use standard query parameters such as `limit` and `offset`, apply defaults in the route handler, and pass pagination options into the shared query function.

Paginated responses must include:

- `data`: The items for the current page.
- `metadata`: Descriptive pagination details. Include `total_items` and `per_page` at minimum. For page-based systems, also include `total_pages` and `current_page`.
- `links`: Full URLs for `next`, `prev`, `first`, and `last` pages so clients can navigate without constructing URLs manually.

```typescript
export const GET = withAuth(async (req, { userId }) => {
  const limit = Number(req.nextUrl.searchParams.get("limit") ?? 20);
  const offset = Number(req.nextUrl.searchParams.get("offset") ?? 0);
  const { items, totalItems } = await getDecksByUser(userId, { limit, offset });

  return NextResponse.json({
    data: items,
    metadata: {
      total_items: totalItems,
      per_page: limit,
    },
    links: {
      next: "https://example.com/api/decks?limit=20&offset=20",
      prev: null,
      first: "https://example.com/api/decks?limit=20&offset=0",
      last: "https://example.com/api/decks?limit=20&offset=80",
    },
  });
});
```

## CORS — Required for All Public Routes

Every route under `src/app/api/` must export an `OPTIONS` handler and include CORS headers so mobile and third-party clients can call it.

```typescript
// src/lib/api/cors.ts
export const CORS_HEADERS = {
  "Access-Control-Allow-Origin": "*",
  "Access-Control-Allow-Methods": "GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS",
  "Access-Control-Allow-Headers": "Content-Type, Authorization",
};

export function withCors(res: NextResponse): NextResponse {
  Object.entries(CORS_HEADERS).forEach(([k, v]) => res.headers.set(k, v));
  return res;
}
```

```typescript
// Preflight — add to every public route file
export async function OPTIONS() {
  return new Response(null, { status: 204, headers: CORS_HEADERS });
}
```

## Dynamic Route Segments

```typescript
// src/app/api/decks/[id]/route.ts
export const GET = withAuth(async (_req, { params, userId }) => {
  const { id } = await params;
  const deck = await getDeckByIdAndUser(Number(id), userId);
  if (!deck) return NextResponse.json({ error: "Not found" }, { status: 404 });
  return NextResponse.json({ data: deck });
});
```

## Server Actions vs. Public API

| Scenario | Use |
|---|---|
| Mutation only used inside the Next.js web app | Server Action |
| Data or mutation needed by mobile / third-party | Public Route Handler |
| Read data only used in Server Components | Direct DB query in Server Component |

Move shared logic to `src/db/queries/` so both Server Actions and Route Handlers call the same function.

## Rules

- Return `{ data }` on success, `{ error }` on failure — always use the envelope shape
- Use `withAuth` wrapper — never repeat the `auth()` + `401` check inline
- Export `OPTIONS` + set CORS headers on every route file
- Paginate every collection route with `limit` and `offset` query parameters
- Include paginated response `metadata` with at least `total_items` and `per_page`
- Include full pagination `links` for `next`, `prev`, `first`, and `last`
- Use consistent standard pagination parameter names: `page`, `pageSize`, `limit`, `offset`, or `cursor`
- Parse query params via `req.nextUrl.searchParams` — never `new URL(req.url)`
- Delegate all DB access to `src/db/queries/*` — no inline Drizzle queries in route files
- Scope every query to `userId` — never expose another user's data
- `params` is a `Promise` in Next.js 15+ — always `await params` before destructuring
